hotspot.title: A Catholic Community of Welcome
hotspot.description: Nazareth Catholic Community is a place of welcome, connecting faith, family and education. Inspired by Jesus of Nazareth and our patrons we are people of justice each committed to building community, nourishing family life and making the world a better place.

hotspot.title: Our Flinders Park Campus
hotspot.description: Our Flinders Park campus welcomes Years 7 - 12 students from the College and their families as well as our wider community engagement programs.

hotspot.title: Drop Down Curtain
hotspot.description: Drop down curtain to separate classes and physical education learning spaces allowing for different sports to be played at the same time

hotspot.title: Sports Program
hotspot.description: Over 600 students compete for our College, with over 60 teams representing girls and boys summer and winter competitions. Opportunities also exist for participation in carnival, knockout competitions and other events. Our outstanding results speak for themselves and have significantly contributed to raising our college profile.

hotspot.title: St Sebastian Centre
hotspot.description: Our St Sebastian Centre includes indoor basketball and netball courts, badminton and volleyball courts, complementing the outdoor courts available for teaching and learning, breaks and cocurricular competitions.

hotspot.title: Our Health and Physical Education Learning Area
hotspot.description: Our curriculum includes a number of invitational Academies aimed at developing students’ skills in AFLW, netball, basketball and soccer with specialist coaches and access to intercol competitions. Students trial for the Academies and this subject is undertaken in place of general Physical Education.

hotspot.title: Oval Space
hotspot.description: Our vast oval space allows for all outdoor team sports to be played as well as outdoor activities at break times and for special events.

hotspot.title: A Vibrant Hub for Our Community
hotspot.description: Creating a faith filled community of welcome and connection is a key part of our mission to nurture family life. Our community cafe’s on both sites are vibrant community hubs for families and community members to connect, meet or just relax with a great coffee and delicious snack or meal.

hotspot.title: Student Involvement in our Cafe
hotspot.description: Barista training is available for Year 12 Students, providing the experience and skills needed for future part time employment. Opportunities are provided for our Inclusive Education students, who regularly cook decadent biscuits to sell in the cafe.

hotspot.title: A Place of Connection
hotspot.description: Our Cafe is open to parents, friends, staff and members of our Community as well as Years 10 - 12 students.

hotspot.title: Catering for Individual Learning Styles
hotspot.description: The Caritas building allows us to cater for a wide range of learning styles in a contemporary, state of the art facility complete with seamless AV integration to support portable and flexible learning.

hotspot.title: Adult Learning Environment
hotspot.description: The flexible learning spaces create an adult learning environment to complement the transition of senior students into tertiary education, whilst allowing teaching staff the ability to create and present varied and diverse learning instructions to accommodate student need.

hotspot.title: Encouraging Self Directed Learning
hotspot.description: Our Caritas building is scattered with kitchenettes throughout the building to assist senior students in self-directed learning and breaks and communal conversation

hotspot.title: Purpose Built Spaces
hotspot.description: The purpose built spaces allow for flexibility for large group and year level or house gatherings across 7 - 12.

hotspot.title: Welcoming Environment for Students
hotspot.description: The wide use of glass sliding doors, and floor to ceiling windows creates vision and a sense of space, and an abundance of natural light, creating a welcoming environment for students.

hotspot.title: Engaging Students’ Creativity
hotspot.description: The expressive arts course engages students’ cognition, imagination, senses and emotions in conceptual and practical ways and involves them thinking kinaesthetically, critically and creatively. Students learn to understand, appreciate and critique the arts by making their own artworks. They also develop their ability to work collaboratively and creatively by devising, rehearsing and performing artworks.

hotspot.title: Versatile Large Space
hotspot.description: Versatile large space which acts as a classroom for Dance and Drama students as well as a theatre for Dance, Drama and Music performances.

hotspot.title: Performing Arts Space
hotspot.description: Equipped with a sprung floor, tarquette, mirrors and black theatre curtains, allows the space to be reconfigured for multiple purposes. Our audio-visual equipment, including sound system, theatre lighting and industry standard lighting control systems has been recently updated as we continue to provide state of the art facilities and resources.

hotspot.title: Performance Opportunities for Students
hotspot.description: The Performing Arts Space (PAS) is used to stage a number of performances throughout the year, including Dance, Drama and Music events. This flexible space also accommodates a range of guest speakers, presentations, workshops, assemblies and other special events

hotspot.title: Special Events
hotspot.description: This flexible space also accommodates a range of guest speakers, presentations, workshops, assemblies and other special events

hotspot.title: Study Support and Flexible Research Spaces
hotspot.description: Years 7 to 12 classes use the various areas in the Veritas Centre in a flexible way for their research and reading needs. It is regularly used as a learning space for group work, study support with staff members, and a quiet space to study, read or browse our magazines and novels.

hotspot.title: Independent Learning
hotspot.description: The Veritas Centre is a communal space used well by students across all year levels where they may choose to either work independently, with a teacher or their peers.

hotspot.title: Staff Support for Students
hotspot.description: Our staff support middle school students on developing note-making and paraphrasing skills, along with correct referencing and bibliography writing as students move into their senior years of schooling. In the senior years a greater emphasis is placed on accessing various online educational resource databases to promote greater depth of academic research.

hotspot.title: Exposure to System Concepts
hotspot.description: Students can develop a broad range of skills and knowledge exploring a range of materials such as wood and metal, in addition to exposure to system concepts such as Computer Aided Design (CAD) and Advanced Manufacturing, Product Design, hydraulic devices and interface components including programmable control devices.

hotspot.title: Design & Technology Facilities
hotspot.description: Our Design and Technology facilities feature 3 main specialty areas. These are: Woodwork, Metalwork and advanced manufacturing, which includes 3D Printers, a Laser Cutter & Vinyl Cutter. Students use Autodesk Fusion 360 to design projects for manufacturing in a variety of materials.

hotspot.title: Participation in Pedal Prix
hotspot.description: Our community have the opportunity each year to participate in Pedal Prix - for students this is offered as a co-curricular sport managed by our Design & Technology staff. Pedal Prix competitions are held across the year in the both city and regional locations.

hotspot.title: Developing Student Techniques and Skills
hotspot.description: Nazareth offers a range of opportunities for students to experience and develop skills with various materials and techniques, including drawing, painting, printmaking, sculpture, mixed media, graphic design and product design. We have a dedicated clay area and kiln for firing ceramic works.

hotspot.title: Industry Standard Resources
hotspot.description: Our students have access to the Adobe Suite, allowing them to work with industry-standard software and explore new media.

hotspot.title: Extending Students’ Learning Opportunities
hotspot.description: Workshops and curriculum extension with professional artists and Annual Art Exhibition. Other opportunities for students to showcase their art work occur throughout the year. . Workshops and curriculum extension opportunities with professional artists, various arts showcases, and displays and an Annual Art Exhibition are regular features of our activities across the year.

hotspot.title: Engaging in Hands On Learning
hotspot.description: The upstairs Salvador Building equipped with three laboratories tailoring to Biology, Chemistry/Physics and general science where students can engage in hands on experiments to enhance their learning.

hotspot.title: Three Laboratories
hotspot.description: Three laboratories tailoring to Biology, Chemistry/Physics and General Science

hotspot.title: Specialist Equipment
hotspot.description: Range of specialist equipment allowing for hands on investigations.

hotspot.title: Teacher Desk
hotspot.description: Science classrooms have teacher desks, with gas and water provisions for science demonstrations.

hotspot.title: Clevertouch Screens
hotspot.description: Clevertouch screens in all classrooms for presentations and interactive learning.

hotspot.title: Engaging in Hands On Learning
hotspot.description: Our science laboratories have a range of specialist equipment allowing for hands on investigations.

hotspot.title: Demonstration Spaces
hotspot.description: All Science classrooms have teacher desks, with gas and water provisions for science demonstrations.

hotspot.title: Integrated Technology
hotspot.description: All teaching and learning areas include Clevertouch screens for presentations and interactive learning.

hotspot.title: Home School Partnership
hotspot.description: A strong partnership between home and school is the key to success so we are a community that is committed to strengthening families’ engagement in their children’s learning and wellbeing.

hotspot.title: Participation in Enrichment Activities
hotspot.description: Students at Nazareth have the opportunity to participate in enrichment activities spanning a variety of disciplines as well as camps and retreats as part of College life.

hotspot.title: Student Leadership Opportunities
hotspot.description: The Student leadership program at Nazareth provides opportunities for students to engage with the school community s well as the wider community. A wide range of leadership opportunities are available for students, with both elected positions and voluntary positions.

hotspot.title: Nazareth Five Habits of Excellence
hotspot.description: At Nazareth, we have adopted the Nazareth Five Habits of Excellence as a ‘roadmap’ to success. The systematic integration of these Habits are a driver for individual student success and is a shared responsibility between home and school to support all learners. Our five Habits are: Attendance, Punctuality, Application, Work Completion and Involvement in the Community.

hotspot.title: Break Time Activities
hotspot.description: The courtyard space encourages a range of positive break time activities such as handball and areas for social conversation and connection.

hotspot.title: Commitment to Social Justice Principles
hotspot.description: We are committed to the social justice principles of the Church, and, as stated in our Mission, are inspired by Jesus of Nazareth and our Patrons... each committed to building community, nourishing family life and making the world a better place. Nazareth Outreach Projects (NOW) are an extension of our values and are supported by the entire community. We have an extensive array of projects we currently support. Our projects extend beyond Australia, with projects internationally, nationally as well as a local level.

hotspot.title: Our House System and Mentor Group Program
hotspot.description: Nazareth has a house system for students, based on our 5 Patrons. Embracing our Catholic identity, the house system creates a sense of connection, belonging and identity for each student in a small group within the College. Each house fosters school ‘spirit’ through various activities and wellbeing programs. Each house is divided into vertically grouped Mentor classes. Our houses are: Catherine, Dominic, MacKillop, McAuley and Romero.

hotspot.title: Building Life Skills and Careers
hotspot.description: Our Technology and Food facilities feature modern food preparation and cooking facilities in the domestic kitchen. Students have access to a shared kitchenette space, which is equipped with tools and equipment to construct basic and extravagant dishes of food.

hotspot.title: Developing Practical Skills
hotspot.description: Technology and Food subjects build life skills for life long learners. This occurs through the knowledge and practical skill development within the topics of food preparation and cooking, nutrition and health, sustainable practices within the home involving food and textiles items, and diversity of food choice within our society.

hotspot.title: Diverse Choice for Learning and Pathways
hotspot.description: Technology and food subjects in the SACE may lead students into a range of future career paths or interests, including Nutrition, Food and Hospitality, Child Studies, Design Technologies

hotspot.title: Commercial Opportunities
hotspot.description: A commercial kitchen with restaurant based cookers, ovens, salamander and food service ware offers our students the opportunity to learn in a real commercial kitchen workspace.

hotspot.title: Creative and Design Resources
hotspot.description: The Textiles room features 22 sewing machines and overlockers which enable students to sew and construct fabric items to a commercial standard, along with resources to support creative design in textiles and the development of educational toys and games for children for SACE Child studies.

hotspot.title: Digital Technologies
hotspot.description:
Our Digital Technologies suite includes the following resources for students to access quality programmes: ·
· Wireless 1080p projectors with sound systems for presentations, group collaboration and student work · Photo quality printers for high quality printing · Desktop computers and screens for ‘high end’ applications · Raspberry Pi mini computers to explore different operating systems · Breakout space for group collaboration · 3d printing for prototyping and developing complete digital solutions · Open layout encourages group collaboration and teamwork.

hotspot.title: Balance of Tradition and Innovation
hotspot.description: Our Music programs at Nazareth aim to provide music education of the highest quality. With a balance of traditional musical concepts and innovative musical experience, we instill in our students the relevance of music education in our society. Our purpose built Music Centre enables students the opportunity to study both Music and Music Technology. A keyboard and music technology lab, large band room, recording studio facility, and instrumental rooms enables students to excel.

hotspot.title: Private Tuition Opportunities
hotspot.description: Instrumental practice rooms for private tuition or student practice and secure instrumental store room for students to safely leave their instruments whilst at school

hotspot.title: Dedicated Recording Studio
hotspot.description: Our dedicated recording studio creates a space for creativity and exploration for isolated recording of vocals and instruments

hotspot.title: Acoustically Treated Band Room
hotspot.description: Acoustically treated band room for ensemble rehearsing catering for a wide variety of styles including rock bands, jazz big bands, choirs, vocal ensembles, percussion groups, concert bands and more

hotspot.title: Professional Standard Concert Grand Piano
hotspot.description: Our professional standard concert grand piano for pianists allows students to practice and perform on. The Grand Piano is used for many special occasions and events.

hotspot.title: Record, Create and Compose
hotspot.description: The music technology room is a purpose-built facilities, with industry standard digital audio workstations for students to record, create and compose music and beats.
